    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so if mechanical tension is the \"main\" driver, does that mean I should just focus on high intensity/heavy weight all the time? or is there a benefit to the metabolic stress part that i'm missing if i only do heavy sets?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Focusing *only* on heavy weight is a recipe for a very slow, very stubborn growth, and you'll miss out on some of the fine-tuning. While mechanical tension is the foundation, a good dose of metabolic stress is crucial for pushing past plateaus. It's like trying to build a fortress with only stone blocks; you get a solid wall, but you don't get the intricate, reinforced defenses that make it truly impenetrable.\n\nTo get the best results, you need to cycle between the two. You can use heavy, low-rep sets to maximize mechanical tension, and then follow up with higher-rep sets or techniques that induce significant metabolic stress. This combination ensures you're hitting both signals that tell the muscle to grow.",
